Crude Oil Volatility Rises as Futures Fall With S&P 500 Index

-- B y   M a r g o t   H a b i b y
-- 
2011-05-03T19:53:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-03/crude-oil-volatility-rises-as-futures-fall-with-s-p-500-index.html
Oil options volatility increased as
the underlying futures fell to the lowest level in two weeks on
a drop in the Standard & Poorâ€™s 500 Index.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
June, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a gauge
of options prices, was 28.9 percent as of 3:30 p.m. in  New York ,
up from 28 percent yesterday.  Crude for June delivery fell $2.47, or 2.2 percent, to
$111.05 a barrel, the lowest settlement since April 19, on the
 New York Mercantile Exchange . Prices have advanced 29 percent in
the past year. Yesterday, futures touched $114.83 a barrel in
intraday trading, the highest level since Sept. 22, 2008.  The most active contracts in electronic trading were June
$120 calls with 2,268 lots changing hands. They dropped 37 cents
to 29 cents a barrel. June $115 calls, the next-most active
option, fell 94 cents to 98 cents a barrel with 1,646 contracts
trading. One contract covers 1,000 barrels of oil.  Nymex distributes real-time data for electronic trading and
releases information on floor trading, where the bulk of options
trading occurs, the next business day.  June $120 calls were the most active options traded in the
previous session, with 5,491 lots changing hands. They decreased
13 cents to 66 cents a barrel. The next-most active option, June
$105 puts, gained 2 cents to 30 cents a barrel on 4,650 lots.  Open interest was highest for December 2012 $80 puts with
44,710 contracts. Next were June $150 calls with 44,109 and
December $120 calls with 38,660.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Margot Habiby in  Dallas  at 
 mhabiby@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Dan Stets at   dstets@bloomberg.net . 